{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"19472321-8125-4bc9-8089-cce06bfdb0c6","content":"No repository-specific docs cover this topic. Here's the general guidance for macOS:\n\n### Recovering a Crash Dump on macOS (NativeAOT, no `createdump`)\n\n1. **Check Apple's Crash Reporter** — macOS automatically captures crash logs under:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name/timestamp.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** (if you need a full memory dump for `lldb`):\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. Core files typically land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Verify `/cores` exists and is writable**:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, you may need to temporarily adjust SIP settings or use `lldb` to attach live:\n   ```bash\n   lldb -p <pid>\n   ```\n\n**Key difference for NativeAOT**: since there's no managed runtime, `createdump` isn't bundled. The native macOS core dump + `lldb` workflow is the standard recovery path.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"46c605d6-bde6-4e53-a1e7-3f8ddd2d8f91","outputTokens":352,"requestId":"6802:2F39F8:AE7A53D:BDA0B98:69FD428F"},"id":"31f85f6b-2da6-498a-9b26-d6dc88cc9a45","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:55:38.489Z","parentId":"4235bfd1-d765-49fc-9e1a-f96edc1f4663"}
